STYLE SECURE ZONE

Secure, smart, seamless shopping a virtual trial room that brings AR + AI to online & offline retail.

Project Summary

Style Secure Zone (a.k.a. VirtualFit) is an end-to-end virtual fitting-room platform that lets users try clothes virtually using AI-driven body recognition and AR/3D rendering, offers size recommendations, and integrates with ecommerce flows so users can purchase directly.

Key highlights:

  • Virtual try-on (photo + live camera) with AR overlay

  • AI body-shape detection + size recommendation engine

  • Unified clothing catalog across retailers

  • In-app shopping checkout & order placement

  • Privacy-first: local processing option + secure uploads

Tech Stack (recommended)

  • Frontend: React (Vite) + TypeScript + Tailwind CSS + Three.js / Model-Viewer / WebXR for AR

  • Backend: Node.js + TypeScript + Express (or Nest) + Prisma (Postgres)

  • AI / Models: Python (PyTorch / TensorFlow) for training, ONNX/TensorFlow.js for inference in-browser/server

  • Storage: PostgreSQL (metadata), S3-compatible object storage (images & 3D assets)

  • Cache/Jobs: Redis + BullMQ for background processing (rendering, model inference)

  • Infra / Container: Docker & Docker Compose, optional Kubernetes

Repo structure (suggested)

/ (root)
frontend/ # React app (Vite)
backend/ # Node.js API (TypeScript)
ai/ # Python model training & conversion
infra/ # docker-compose, k8s manifests
scripts/ # utility scripts (seed, build-models)
README.md

Quickstart Prerequisites

  • Node.js >= 18

  • npm / yarn

  • Docker & Docker Compose (for containerized run)

  • Python 3.10+ (for AI training & conversion)

  • PostgreSQL (local or Docker)

Local development (recommended flow)

1) Clone the repo

git clone https://github.com/<your-org>/style-secure-zone.git
cd style-secure-zone

2) Environment

Create .env files in frontend/ and backend/ (examples in .env.example).

Example root .env.example (place in backend/):

# backend/.env
DATABASE_URL=postgresql://postgres:postgres@localhost:5432/style_secure
REDIS_URL=redis://localhost:6379
S3_ENDPOINT=http://localhost:9000
S3_BUCKET=style-assets
JWT_SECRET=super-secret-key
NODE_ENV=development
PORT=4000

3) Start services with Docker Compose (DB + Redis + MinIO)

# from project root
docker compose up -d --build

4) Backend install & run

cd backend
# install
npm install
# run database migrations (Prisma example)
npx prisma migrate dev --name init
# seed (if available)
npm run seed
# dev server (hot reload)
npm run dev
# prod build & start
npm run build
npm start

If using Sequelize or TypeORM replace npx prisma migrate dev with the relevant migration command.

5) Frontend install & run

cd frontend
npm install
# dev server (hot reload)
npm run dev
# build for production
npm run build
# preview prod build
npm run preview

6) AI service training & export (optional)

cd ai
# create venv (recommended)
python -m venv .venv
source .venv/bin/activate # macOS / Linux
.venv\Scripts\activate # Windows
pip install -r requirements.txt
# train a model (example)
python train.py --config configs/body_shape.yaml
# convert to ONNX / TFJS for inference
python export.py --model checkpoints/latest.pt --format onnx

Tests & Linters

# backend (Jest + ESLint + Prettier)
cd backend
npm run test
npm run lint
npm run format:check

# frontend
cd frontend
npm run test
npm run lint

Docker commands (full-stack)

# build all images
docker compose build
# run all services in foreground
docker compose up
# run in background
docker compose up -d
# stop
docker compose down
# rebuild and recreate
docker compose up -d --build --force-recreate

Background jobs & rendering (examples)

  • Use a worker process to handle heavy tasks (3D rendering, model inference):

# start worker (example using BullMQ)
cd backend
npm run worker

Common npm scripts (example package.json snippets)

// backend/package.json (scripts)
{
"dev": "TS_NODE_PROJECT=./tsconfig.json ts-node-dev --respawn src/server.ts",
"build": "tsc -p .",
"start": "node dist/server.js",
"migrate": "npx prisma migrate deploy",
"seed": "node dist/prisma/seed.js",
"worker": "node dist/worker.js",
"lint": "eslint . --ext .ts",
"test": "jest"
}

// frontend/package.json (scripts)
{
"dev": "vite",
"build": "vite build",
"preview": "vite preview",
"lint": "eslint src --ext .ts,.tsx",
"test": "vitest"
}

Security & Privacy notes

  • Offer local-processing toggle for sensitive photos (process images only on-device using TFJS / WebAssembly when user enables it).

  • Secure uploads with presigned S3 URLs.

  • Encrypt sensitive data at rest and in transit (HTTPS, TLS).

Example API endpoints (backend)

POST /api/auth/login # login
POST /api/users # create user
GET /api/catalog # list clothing
GET /api/catalog/:id # item details (3D model links)
POST /api/tryon # upload image or provide camera stream metadata -> returns render URL / mask
POST /api/recommend # body-shape + size suggestion
POST /api/checkout # create order

Debugging tips

  • Check worker logs for rendering errors.

  • Ensure S3 credentials are correct for asset retrieval.

  • Use ngrok for local testing of webhooks and mobile camera streams.
